@VersayceNomi @BuzzFeed So, when A and C are sued they can say "we deny your claims, prove them." It forces the Plaintiff to bear the burden of proof required by the Rules.

@VersayceNomi @BuzzFeed Yes, I mixed 3 types of negligence, but the fact that A was driving without a license isn't false. C, even if they knew A didn't have a license, isn't liable for negligent entrustment if the injury wasn't caused by As lack of drivers license. It was caused by Bs negligence.

@VersayceNomi @BuzzFeed For example: A driver doesn't have a driver's license. B runs a red light and hits A. B then sues A and C who lent A the car claiming that A and C are liable because A didn't have a driver's license. Are A and C liable for Bs damages? Probably not.

@VersayceNomi @BuzzFeed Because while a fact alleged in the petition may be true, that doesn't mean the fact meets the level of proof required to establish the elements of a cause of action. When the Plaintiff bears the burden of proof, they have to show why those facts create liability and the damages.
